<ArticleLayout
  title="Setting Up a Baby Change Area at Home"
  description="Plan a baby change area around change tables or mats, nappies, wipes, bins, cleaning, rentals and smaller homes."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery change area with baby supplies, soft light and practical storage"
>
  <p>
    A change table can look like a straightforward purchase until nappies, wipes, creams,
    spare clothes, laundry, spills, bins and night changes all meet in the same small area.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the surface is too high, the space is cramped or the supplies sit behind you, the
    frustration shows up several times a day. Decide where changes will happen and who will
    do them most often before choosing the furniture.
  </p>
  <p>
    The sections below compare change tables, mats, caddies and bins in the context of the
    room rather than as a nursery shopping list.
  </p>

  <h2>The change table is optional</h2>
  <p>
    A good baby change station should make repeated daily changes simpler, safer and easier
    to clean. For many Australian homes, the most practical setup is not necessarily the
    largest change table.
  </p>
  <p>
    It may be a stable change surface, a washable mat, nappies and wipes within reach, a
    sensible bin nearby and enough room for adults to move without blocking drawers, doors or
    walkways. A more expensive nursery unit is not automatically better if it overwhelms the
    room, is awkward to clean or will only be useful for a short period.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose the place before the furniture</h2>
  <p>
    Location should come before furniture. Some households use the nursery. Others change the
    baby in the parents' bedroom, bathroom, laundry, living area or a grandparents' spare
    room. Small apartments may need one compact setup plus a portable caddy rather than a
    full change station in every room.
  </p>
  <p>Before choosing the spot, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether the room has enough light for day and night changes</li>
    <li>whether nappies, wipes and spare clothes can be kept close</li>
    <li>whether dirty clothes can reach the laundry without sitting around</li>
    <li>whether the bin can be emptied easily</li>
    <li>whether the floor is easy to clean after spills</li>
    <li>whether doors, drawers, wardrobes or walkways will be blocked</li>
    <li>whether the setup suits renters, apartments or shared bedrooms</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For the broader baby setup, start with the <a href="/categories/nursery-kids/">Nursery & Kids</a>{" "}
    category or the <a href="/guides/nursery-essentials-for-australian-homes/">nursery essentials guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Do you need a dedicated change table?</h2>
  <p>
    A dedicated change table can provide a comfortable height, shelves and a clear routine.
    It can also take up valuable floor space and may have a short useful life. In compact
    rooms, that matters.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some households prefer a change mat on top of a suitable dresser, if the dresser and mat
    are used according to manufacturer instructions. Others use a portable mat on a safe, low
    surface for occasional changes. The point is not to improvise. It is to choose a setup
    that suits the room, the adults using it and the product instructions.
  </p>
  <p>
    Always check product dimensions, weight limits, straps, placement, cleaning directions
    and use instructions before relying on any change surface.
  </p>

  <h2>Change table, mat on a dresser or portable mat?</h2>
  <p>
    Each option has strengths and limits. The right choice depends on your room and routine.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Dedicated change table: organised and purpose-built, but often bulky.</li>
    <li>Mat on a dresser: saves space where it is suitable, but needs careful setup and manufacturer guidance.</li>
    <li>Portable foldable mat: useful for small homes, outings and occasional changes, but less organised.</li>
    <li>Floor-level change mat: lower to the ground, but may be uncomfortable for adults.</li>
    <li>Bathroom or laundry setup: practical for cleaning, but may be cold, cramped or inconvenient at night.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For changes away from home, the <a href="/guides/baby-outing-essentials-what-to-pack-before-leaving-the-house/">baby outing essentials guide</a>{" "}
    covers travel mats, nappy bags and what to keep easy to reach.
  </p>

  <h2>Height, stability, reach and everyday safety habits</h2>
  <p>
    Height matters because change stations are used repeatedly. Too low can be uncomfortable.
    Too high can feel awkward or hard to control. Stability matters more than styling, and a
    clear surface matters more than decorative extras.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before each change, have supplies ready. Keep one hand on the baby when using a raised
    change surface, and do not leave a baby unattended on a raised surface. Keep cords,
    heaters, curtains, blinds, lotions, cleaning products, small items and heavy objects out
    of reach.
  </p>
  <p>
    Secure heavy furniture according to manufacturer guidance, and follow the product's
    assembly, use and cleaning instructions. If you have concerns about baby safety, injury,
    skin irritation, feeding, sleep or development, speak with a GP, child health nurse,
    paediatrician or relevant qualified professional.
  </p>

  <h2>What to keep within arm's reach</h2>
  <p>
    The most useful change station is usually simple. Keep frequently used items close, and
    store bulk extras somewhere else so the surface does not become crowded.
  </p>
  <p>Useful items may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>nappies</li>
    <li>wipes</li>
    <li>change mat liners or covers</li>
    <li>barrier cream if used</li>
    <li>spare clothes</li>
    <li>burp cloths or small towels</li>
    <li>nappy bags or disposal bags if used</li>
    <li>hand sanitiser if used, kept safely out of baby's reach</li>
    <li>a laundry basket or wet bag</li>
    <li>a bin or nappy disposal system</li>
    <li>a small caddy for moving supplies around the home</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For a shorter item-by-item list, see the <a href="/guides/nappy-change-station-checklist/">nappy change station checklist</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Nappy bins, odour and cleaning</h2>
  <p>
    Bin choice matters, but emptying frequency usually matters more than product claims. An
    ordinary bin, lidded bin or nappy disposal system can all be workable depending on space,
    budget and routine.
  </p>
  <p>
    Warm weather can make odour more noticeable, especially in apartments or bedrooms with
    limited airflow. Avoid placing bins where they block walkways, sit in direct sun or sit
    too close to heaters.
  </p>
  <p>
    Wipe-clean surfaces are often more useful than decorative baskets that are hard to clean.
    Liners, covers and mats should be easy to wash and dry. Wet nappies, soiled clothing and
    damp wraps also need a practical laundry path, especially in humid or wet weather.
  </p>

  <h2>Change stations for small homes, rentals and apartments</h2>
  <p>
    Small homes often need a change setup that works hard without dominating the room.
    Compact change tables, mats on dressers where suitable, portable caddies and
    repurposable storage can all make sense.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters should avoid unnecessary drilling unless approved. Wall-mounted or fold-down
    options may suit some homes only if they are suitable, allowed and installed according to
    the product requirements. Do not buy bulky nursery furniture if it blocks wardrobes,
    doors or movement.
  </p>
  <p>
    In apartments, think about bin odour, laundry access, noise at night and limited drying
    space. A smaller setup that is easy to clean often works better than a styled but crowded
    nursery corner.
  </p>

  <h2>Night-time changes and shared spaces</h2>
  <p>
    Night changes need to be simple and predictable. Keep supplies in the same place, keep
    walkways clear and avoid noisy bins, rattly drawers or difficult packaging if the change
    area is in a shared bedroom.
  </p>
  <p>
    Soft lighting may help adults see what they are doing, but this guide is not sleep
    advice. The practical aim is a calmer room that is easier to move through when people are
    tired.
  </p>
  <p>
    Decide where dirty clothes, wraps or linen will go during the night. A small basket or
    wet bag near the change area can prevent items being left on the floor until morning.
  </p>

  <h2>Surfaces that can cope with mess</h2>
  <p>
    Change areas get messy. Waterproof mats, surfaces that can be wiped down, washable covers and tubs
    usually work better than materials that trap odour or take too long to dry.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying mats, covers or organisers, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether the surface can be wiped clean</li>
    <li>whether covers fit your washing and drying routine</li>
    <li>whether fabric baskets will cope with spills</li>
    <li>whether plastic tubs would be easier to clean</li>
    <li>whether timber or painted furniture may mark if wet items sit on it</li>
    <li>whether the product has clear cleaning instructions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Spare covers can be useful if they are genuinely used, but they also add laundry. Check
    drying time before buying more than you can easily wash and reset.
  </p>

  <h2>Trade-offs worth knowing</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Dedicated change table versus floor space.</li>
    <li>Dresser-top mat versus careful setup requirements.</li>
    <li>Portable mat versus less organisation.</li>
    <li>Decorative baskets versus tubs that can be wiped clean.</li>
    <li>Large nappy bin versus room impact.</li>
    <li>Open shelves versus dust and visual clutter.</li>
    <li>Fabric covers versus more laundry.</li>
    <li>Compact setup versus fewer supplies on hand.</li>
    <li>Higher surface versus adult comfort and safety habits.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The right choice depends on the household. A smaller setup that is stable, cleanable and
    easy to restock can be more useful than a large unit that makes the room harder to use.
  </p>

  <h2>Before bringing anything home</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Decide where most changes will happen.</li>
    <li>Measure the available floor or dresser space.</li>
    <li>Check whether doors, drawers, wardrobes or walkways will be blocked.</li>
    <li>Check product dimensions, weight limits and manufacturer instructions.</li>
    <li>Make sure the change surface feels stable.</li>
    <li>Choose a height that suits the adults using it most.</li>
    <li>Keep nappies, wipes, spare clothes and disposal options within reach.</li>
    <li>Choose surfaces that can be wiped down where mess is likely.</li>
    <li>Check whether covers, liners or mats are easy to wash and dry.</li>
    <li>Think about bin placement and odour in warm weather.</li>
    <li>Avoid unnecessary drilling in rentals unless approved.</li>
    <li>Keep cords, small items, cleaning products and heavy objects away from baby's reach.</li>
    <li>Do not leave a baby unattended on a raised change surface.</li>
    <li>For baby health, skin, feeding, sleep or safety concerns, seek qualified advice.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Where the setup becomes awkward</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying a large change table before measuring the room.</li>
    <li>Choosing furniture only because it matches the nursery.</li>
    <li>Forgetting where dirty clothes and nappies will go.</li>
    <li>Keeping wipes or nappies out of reach.</li>
    <li>Blocking wardrobe doors, drawers or walkways.</li>
    <li>Choosing baskets and organisers that are hard to clean.</li>
    <li>Ignoring odour during hot weather.</li>
    <li>Buying a product with a short useful life when space is tight.</li>
    <li>Overloading the change surface with decor.</li>
    <li>Assuming a mat can be used on a dresser without checking product instructions.</li>
    <li>Forgetting how the area will work at night.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What may suit different homes</h2>
  <p>
    If product examples are added later, they should stay tied to suitability rather than
    making one setup sound right for every household.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>For small homes: compact mats, portable caddies and repurposable storage may be worth considering.</li>
    <li>For renters: freestanding furniture and setups that do not alter the wall are usually easier to take with you.</li>
    <li>For shared bedrooms: quiet drawers, simple lighting and contained supplies can matter more than a full nursery setup.</li>
    <li>For grandparents' homes: a portable mat and small supply caddy may be enough for occasional care.</li>
    <li>For easier cleaning: mats and tubs that can be wiped down are usually a better choice than decorative baskets.</li>
    <li>For a setup near the laundry: water and washing access can help, but comfort and convenience at night still matter.</li>
    <li>For use after the baby stage: choose furniture that can become ordinary storage if space and budget allow.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Choose for repeated use, not appearance</h2>
  <p>
    A baby change station does not need to be elaborate. It needs to be stable, easy to
    clean, well placed and stocked with the items used repeatedly each day.
  </p>
  <p>
    The setup that works during tired mornings and night changes will usually serve the
    household better than a bulky nursery unit chosen mainly for appearance. Start with where
    changes will happen, measure the space, keep supplies within reach and choose materials
    that can handle real daily mess.
  </p>
  <p>
    For bath-time setup after changes, see <a href="/guides/baby-bath-time-essentials/">Baby Bath Time Essentials</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Use the current change-table safety advice</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying or using a raised change surface, read the{" "}
    <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/keep-baby-safe/bathe-and-change-baby-safely" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC Product Safety bathing and changing guide</a>.
    Check warnings and assembly instructions, keep the setup within arm's reach and never rely on
    the furniture or restraints as a substitute for supervision.
  </p>

